Research

I trained in evolutionary biology, specializing in quantitative genetics — a field using advanced statistical methods to study the components underlying variation within traits and covariation between traits, in the light of evolution. I used these approaches to study the evolution of sex differences, specifically exploring questions around

  • the extent of genetic constraint on the evolution of sex differences
  • the role of sex chromosomes in the evolution of sex differences
  • the effect of mutation and environmental change on variance-covariance matrices

This work started during my Bachelors and Masters degrees at the University of Exeter, working in the labs of David Hosken, Nina wedell and John Hunt as a voluntary research assistant. From there, I moved to Uppsala University in Sweden to complete a PhD under the supervision of Urban Friberg and then a postdoc at Turku University in Finland in Virpi Lummaa’s research group. Finally, funding from the Swedish research council took me back to Uppsala University as a Postdoctoral Research Fellow, and included almost two years at the University of Queensland, Australia, working with Steve Chenoweth.

For family reasons, I decided to move into the private sector in 2020. However, I continue to perform research in evolutionary quantitative genetics and I am open to further collaborations — reach out to me if you have something in mind!
